\begin_body

\begin_layout Chapter
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Standard model and Quantum Chromodynamics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Standard Model of particle physics is a theory concerning the electromagneti
c, weak, and strong nuclear interactions, which explains how the basic building
 blocks of matter interact.
 The Standard Model includes members of several classes of elementary particles:
 12 elementary particles of spin 1/2 known as fermions, 4 gauge bosons of
 spin 1 who carry the force of fundamental interactions and Higgs boson
 of spin 0 which interacts with elementary particles and gives them mass.
 The 12 fermions includes 6 quarks (up (
\emph on
u
\emph default
), down (
\emph on
d
\emph default
), strange (
\emph on
s
\emph default
), charm (
\emph on
c
\emph default
), top (
\emph on
t
\emph default
), bottom (
\emph on
b
\emph default
)), and 6 leptons (electron (
\emph on
e
\emph default
), muon (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

), tau (
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

) and the corresponding neutrinos).
 The 4 gauge bosons are gluon (
\emph on
g
\emph default
), photon (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

), 
\emph on
W
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
Z
\emph default
 bosons, which are classified by the fundamental force they carry.
 Gluons mediate the strong interactions between color charged particles
 (quarks).
 Gluons also carry color charge, so they can also interact with themselves.
 The strong interaction are described by the theory of quantum chromodynamics.
 The electric charged particles interact through the electromagnetic force
 mediated by Photons which is well-described by the theory of quantum electrodyn
amics.
 The weak force is carried by 
\emph on
W
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
Z
\emph default
 bosons.
 They are grouped with photons, as collectively mediation the electroweak
 interaction.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SM"

\end_inset

 shows the particles generations and interactions between them.
 Fermions interact with each other through the fundamental force carried
 by gauge bosons and form the matter world.
 On 14 March 2013, the Higgs boson was tentatively confirmed to exist.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

