\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Deconfinement and QGP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another important feature of QCD is confinement which lead to the absence
 of direct observation of isolated quarks and gluons in the experiment.
 The confinement is because gluons who carry the force have color charge
 and thus can interact with itself.
 Due to the property of the running QCD coupling constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}$
\end_inset

, when two quarks are separated from each other, the force between them
 grows stronger as the distance increasing.
 When the energy is enough, a new quark/anti-quark pair is created from
 the vacuum.
 As result of this, the quarks and gluons are confined inside hadrons, and
 when quarks is created in high energy experiment, instead of seeing the
 individual quarks, only cluster of color neutral hadrons are observed.
 This process is called hadronization.
 On the other hand, when the system is at extreme temperature or high energy
 density, such like the universe in a few microsecond after the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Big Bang
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, due to the asymptotic freedom, the interaction between partons (quarks/anti-qu
arks and gluons) is very weak and the partons can travel over larger distances
 of the size of a nucleon (~1 fm).
 The quarks and gluons are deconfined and form a thermalized state known
 as Quark-Gluon Plasma (QGP) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevLett.34.1353"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lattice QCD calculations expect a phase transition from the hadronic
 phase into the QGP phase.
 The
\emph on
 Polyakov loop operator,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L=\frac{1}{3}{\rm tr}\left(\mathcal{P}e^{ig\intop_{0}^{\beta}A_{4}(x,\tau)d\tau}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\emph default
is believed as a observable for the phase transition.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ptxs"

\end_inset

 left shows the Polyakov loop operator expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle L\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and its temperature derivative as a function of the lattice coupling 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=6/g^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 At small temperature, a vanishing thermal expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle L\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 of Polyakov loop operator indicates infinite energy for a free quark, or
 in another word, quark is confined.
 At high temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle L\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 increase rapidly to a nonzero value, its derivative shows a sharp peak
 at a critical coupling 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{cr}$
\end_inset

.
 This indicates that quark is deconfined at the corresponding critical temperatu
re 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{cr}$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Phase_diagram"

\end_inset

 shows the phase diagram of strongly interacting matter in temperature vs.
 baryon chemical potential plane (
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{B}$
\end_inset

).
 The lattice QCD calculations tell us the phase transition alone the temperature
 axis (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{B}$
\end_inset

 = 0), with a crossover transition from hadron resonance gas to a QGP phase
 at a temperature about 154 MeV.
 On other hand, QCD based models indicate that the crossover transition
 ends at a critical point at high 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{B}$
\end_inset

 and becomes first order transition 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevD.78.074507,PhysRevC.79.015202"

\end_inset

.
 However, the locations of the phase boundary and the critical point in
 this framework depend on model assumptions.
 One of the main aim of high-energy heavy-ion collision experiments is to
 explore the QCD phase diagram, to locate the position of critical point,
 and to determine the QCD phase boundary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../fig/1.Introduction/phase_transition_xsymmtry.png
	lyxscale 50
	width 90text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Left panel: the expectation value of Polyakov loop 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle L\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and its temperature derivative (Polyakov loop susceptibility 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{L}$
\end_inset

) as a function of the lattice coupling 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=6/g^{2}$
\end_inset

 which is related to the temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 (larger 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 correspond to larger 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

).
 Right panel: the chiral condensate (the scalar quark density) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \bar{\psi}\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and the negative of its temperature derivative (chiral susceptibility 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{m}$
\end_inset

) as a function of temperature.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevD.50.6954,Heinz:fk"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

